english:
  title: Postscript to a Poem Presented to Kim, the Judge
  author: Lee Sek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The customs of mourning have long fallen into disuse. In my travels through the Central Lands years ago, I witnessed scholars and officials wearing mourning garments and sashes while partaking of wine and meat—a sight that seemed most peculiar at first. Yet when I observed how they wept morning and evening without fail for three full years, and how even the most hardened men could not help but be moved to tears upon hearing their lamentations, I came to understand that the noble principles of China's social order had not entirely vanished.

    Since Goryeo's founding through the Zhou dynasty's enfeoffment of the sage Jizi, it has transformed into a civilized realm, establishing a three-year mourning period. Yet after merely one hundred days, people return to auspicious affairs. While abstaining from pungent vegetables is commendable, eating rice remains unchanged. The selection of burial grounds and funeral rites largely accord with Chinese practice, yet the rites of early and late offering have disappeared. The lesser and greater sacrifices, the final sacrifice—these observances remain, yet there is no daily weeping. Thus people cannot perceive that one still dwells in mourning.

    Considering this, the gains and losses of mourning rites under heaven are roughly balanced. Examining our kingdom's chart of mourning vestments: "For the three-year mourning, one receives leave for one hundred days, with all remaining periods declining accordingly." If indeed one hundred days constitutes three years, then the sacrifices should fall within that period. Yet this is not so. One year marks the lesser sacrifice, two years the greater sacrifice, and three months thereafter the final sacrifice—all with leave granted. This clearly amounts to twenty-seven months.

    Moreover, leave is prescribed for those in official service. When leave expires, one must resume duties. Since the auspicious and inauspicious cannot share vessels, one cannot but remove mourning garments. But why should others do so? Though vestments are removed, one ought not drink wine, eat meat, nor frequent the inner chambers—maintaining mental mourning for three years. Yet people say, "My leave is ended, my mourning removed," and restraint ceases. This is mere heedlessness.

    Tracing this fault's origin: it lies in official leave, extended through premature restoration to service, imitated by those without position, and further imitated by common folk. Through habit and convenience, the error became invisible. Thus only those keeping vigil at tombs truly complete three years.

    The tomb houses the physical form; the spirit returns to the home, appeased through the three offerings. With household temples now abandoned, the spirit wanders everywhere, dependent upon descendants. Where descendants dwell, there the spirit abides. Thus weeping and offerings morning and evening, performed at the grave rather than home—what harm? Though differing somewhat from the sage's precepts, in this age when ritual has crumbled, to fulfill the deepest filial duty and repay the debt of three years in one's parents' care surpasses all other ways. The state thus marks such dwellings, and people call them filial sons. Even should the sage return, this would not change.

    The Kim clan of Nagan is a great family of the three kingdoms. The brothers were renowned for their filial devotion to their mother. In the winter of Shinchuk, when bandits invaded the capital, they escorted their mother southward. The elder brother, the Rector of Studies, fell ill on the journey and passed away. Their mother, deeply grieved, soon followed. The younger brother, the Judge, enshrined their remains at a villa on Taesan Mountain, wailing day and night, never leaving the mourning ground for months. After the burial, he dwelt nearby to complete the full term—this is what I meant by the sage's way unchanged.

    The Master Taman, White, composed the virtue of filial piety, which scholars sang in praise. I, who merely await the end of my leave before returning to service, read this work and could not restrain my sorrow. Thus I record the gains and losses of mourning rites, their decline's source, and how vigil at the tomb expresses the truth of feeling—this is my postscript.
  footnotes:
    - 'Jizi (箕子): The legendary sage enshrined by the Zhou dynasty, traditionally credited as the cultural ancestor of Goryeo'
    - 'The three offerings (三虞): Early Confucian rites to comfort the spirit after death'
    - 'Household temples (家廟): The ancestral shrine where spirits were traditionally maintained and honored'
    - 'Taesan: A mountain region near the capital, suggesting the family''s rural estate'
